Note: PT says that it is challenging to read the subtitles and take in the information from the video. They are focused on the subtitles being correct that it is distracting from the video itself.
PT states the text size is a good size, not too large or too small. PT states that it is not transcribing all the correct words — for example the video said “wait” but it transcribed as “weight”.
Sometimes the transcript will only transcribe part of the word — like 3 letters of the word rather than the whole thing.

Asked the participant if the transcription was still working well even with the background noise and voices. They said that the background noise has not been an issue. It is transcribing well. We then tested it. We had the pt watch the video and transcription while moderators asked the pt a question. The pt stated the transcription picked up a couple of words from the moderator but definitely not all of them, the transcription stayed with the video more.
PT said that when they hold the phone closer to them, the transcription does not always work. When they hold it farther away, it does work…

PT said that when saying “hey meta” and asks a question, when they are finished with the question they can not say anything else because meta thinks that the pt is still talking to meta (even though the pt isn’t).
We had pt ask meta to identify an exercise movement being performed by a moderator and meta was able to correctly identify the movement in motion.
Sometimes meta gets overwhelmed with extra noise and quits on the participant after asking a question. When the environment noise is less, it is more accurate and doesn’t quit.
There is some connectivity issues with the video call. The PT is having trouble seeing the caller. It seems to be frozen or delayed image movement
PT really likes the video call on the glasses because they never have to look away from the person during the call. They think that it would really helpful when shopping and showing people things
Pt wishes they could scroll through the photos sent to them in WhatsApp instead of having to go back out and find a photo in the thread again.
PT states that the color and details in the photos accurately represent the colors and details of the legos on the table and they are able to differentiate different shades of the same color.

Participant is able to discern details from the images like the text in the upper left corner denoting the required number of Lego pieces, the number of circles on each Lego piece, and differences in shapes.
Participant is viewing images using black solid TV background
Participant actually decides that shapes are not always easily identifiable against each other but other details are helpful in determining the correct Lego piece

Participant notices that the exact location that each Lego piece should be placed in is not easily identifiable through the images and that details like the number of circles on each piece is helpful in determining the correct location
PT would pick having a larger display screen versus the ability to zoom in during the Lego activity. But not necessarily for the other activities
During the building of the second dinosaur legos, the pt had trouble finding a piece due to the colors now looking different in color. It could be the lighting of the photos taken…
Battery at 15%
Spotify randomly started playing music

When asked about the perception of specific colors displayed on MR screen in comparison to Lego pieces on table, participant decided that they interpret the orange Lego as orange on screen but could truly understand how others might perceive that orange as red
